# Command hexyl

## What does this command do:

A command-line colorized hex viewer

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `sudo dnf install hexyl`
For Raspberry Pi install using: `sudo apt-get install hexyl`
For Mac install using: `brew install hexyl`

## Command path

For Fedora run: `/usr/bin/hexyl`
For Raspberry Pi run: `/usr/bin/hexyl`
For Mac run: `/opt/homebrew/bin/hexyl`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://github.com/sharkdp/hexyl

## Command options

# View a file
hexyl <file>

# Read from stdin
cat <file> | hexyl

# Only show the first N bytes (supports units: kB, MiB, 0xff, etc.)
hexyl -n 256 <file>
hexyl --length=4KiB <file>

# Skip the first N bytes
hexyl -s 64 <file>

# Show all lines (disable squeezing of repeated lines)
hexyl -v <file>

# Plain output (no color, no border, no character panel, no position)
hexyl -p <file>

# Hide the character panel on the right
hexyl --no-characters <file>

# Hide the position panel on the left
hexyl -P <file>

# Control border style
hexyl --border=ascii <file>
hexyl --border=none <file>

# Control color output
hexyl --color=never <file>
hexyl --color=auto <file>

# Group bytes together (1, 2, 4, or 8) with endianness control
hexyl -g 4 <file>
hexyl -g 4 --endianness=little <file>

# Change number base (binary, octal, decimal, hexadecimal)
hexyl -b octal <file>

# Set number of hex panels
hexyl --panels=auto <file>

# Add offset to displayed positions
hexyl -o 0x100 <file>

# Set terminal width explicitly
hexyl --terminal-width=120 <file>

# Change character table
hexyl --character-table=ascii <file>
hexyl --character-table=codepage-437 <file>
